        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>As demonstrated by our numerical model illustrated in the scientific section, the expected line strength is at least 12 K. However, for our purposes it is not sufficient to detect the line, but we want to reveal the dip in the double peak at the line center. According to our calculations, the difference between the peaks and the dip is about 6 K and we want to attain a S/N=10, which implies a 1sigma RMS of 0.6 K. According to the OT time estimator, this requires 1.41 hours on-source, after smoothing the recombination line spectrum to 4 km/s. This resolution will suffice to resolve the double peak in a line as wide as ~20 km/s FWHM.

Time constraints: None

User defined calibrations: None</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will cover the H26alpha line with a 937.5 MHz band unit, with double polarization and a spectral resolution of 1.9 MHz. We plan to smooth the H26alpha spectrum to 4 km/s, which will still suffice to resolve the broad profile (FWHM=20 km/s). The correlator setup is chosen in such a way to cover other potentially interesting (hot core) tracers such as the 13CH3CN(19-18), C33S(7-6), CH3CCH(20-19), CN(3-2) and HCN(4-3) transitions. We have also selected a broad band unit (2 GHz) to measure the continuum level from  the line-free channels. From Beltran et al (2007) we extrapolate a free-free, optically thin flux of 70 mJy at 354 GHz for the HII region and thus plan to use this compact emission to self-calibrate our data.

Data rate: We have spectral averaged the data of some spectral units to lower the data rate (below 12 MB/s). The final spectral resolution (between 0.5 and 1.0 km/s) is still good enough to resolve potential interesting (hot core) tracers, and does not represent a problem for the H26alpha line.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We plan to image the H26alpha recombination line (353.623 GHz; band 7) with 0.12 arcsec resolution towards the hypercompact HII region G24.78+0.08 A1. Note that the source will be only barely resolved (the HII region size is about 0.15 arcsec), but this will suffice for our purpose to obtain an H26alpha spectrum towards the hypercompact HII region with the best possible S/N (as demonstrated in the scientific section). Being the HII region only 0.15 arcsec in diameter, we have no problem with extended structures.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
