    <prp:abstract>We propose to image the H26alpha recombination line in band 7 with the goal to establish the kinematics of the ionised gas in the hypercompact HII region G24.78+0.08 A1. High-angular resolution observations of the free-free continuum emission have revealed that this unique HII region (which lies at the center of a rotating and infalling hot molecular core) has a shell-like morphology, with several water maser spots distributed along the border. The 3-D velocity field traced by the masers can be interpreted either as expansion with a dynamical lifetime of only 50 years, or as drift of the HII region with respect to the surrounding molecular core, from SW to NE. A measurement of the profile of the H26alpha line towards the center of the HII region will suffice to discriminate between these two possible scenarios. In fact, if the ionised gas lies in an expanding shell, the line should be double peaked. Should expansion be confirmed, our observations will set constraints on the different theoretical models proposed to explain the evolution of HII regions in their first evolutionary stages.</prp:abstract>
